    "quirks": [
      "search_text comprised solely of spaces returns office results instead of being rejected",
      "Non-string search_text values are stringified; booleans, numbers, and arrays succeed unexpectedly",
      "limit coerces numeric strings, floats, and booleans; negative values suppress top-tier results while still returning sub-tier and office matches",
      "Passing limit as null or an object yields HTML 500 responses",
      "Office entries often include null names even though docs specify strings",
      "Some top-tier agencies return null abbreviations and empty office arrays",
      "messages array has been empty in all successful responses so far"
    ],
    "risks": [
      "Invalid limit types (null/object) cause HTML 500 responses that may break JSON clients",
      "High or coerced limits can return hundreds of office objects, many with null names; consumers must handle sparse data",
      "Negative or coerced limits can silently remove top-tier results while leaving large sub-tier and office sets",
      "Automatic stringification of non-string search_text values can let unexpected user input produce surprising matches"
    ],
    "gaps": [
      "Unknown whether an upper bound on limit exists; calls through 1000 succeeded without warnings or truncation notices",
      "Unable to observe non-empty messages even with high limits and coerced inputs; trigger conditions remain unclear",
      "Ranking and ordering heuristics for returned matches not documented"
    ],
